In [9]:
#step one of the Engle/Granger two step method
#function that regresses one series on another
def reg(x,y):
    #using statsmodels linear regression function
    regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    #builds a df of the constant crossing over the y axis
    x_constant = pd.concat([x,pd.Series([1]*len(x), index = x.index)], axis=1)
    #fitting the model for each value to its y value
    regr.fit(x_constant, y)
    #y=mx+b
    beta = regr.coef_[0]
    alpha = regr.intercept_
    #this is the formula to calculate residuals
    spread = y - x*beta - alpha
    return spread

# convert the array of scaled data into a matrix
#as a whole, this function basically creates new independent and dependent variables 
# by predicting ones value based on the time stamp
def create_dataset(dataset, time_step=1):
    dataX, dataY = [], []
    for i in range(len(dataset)-time_step-1):
        a = dataset[i:(i+time_step), 0]
        dataX.append(a)
        dataY.append(dataset[i + time_step, 0])
    return np.array(dataX), np.array(dataY)

### Plotting ## taken directly from Krish Naik's tutorial --visual aesthetics updated by me
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
# shift train predictions for plotting
look_back=100
trainPredictPlot = np.empty_like(df1)
trainPredictPlot[:, :] = np.nan
trainPredictPlot[look_back:len(train_predict)+look_back, :] = train_predict
# shift test predictions for plotting
testPredictPlot = np.empty_like(df1)
testPredictPlot[:, :] = np.nan
testPredictPlot[len(train_predict)+(look_back*2)+1:len(df1)-1, :] = test_predict
# plot baseline and predictions
plt.title('train/test predictions overlay')
plt.plot(scaler.inverse_transform(df1), label = 'Actual Series', color='green', alpha=.3)
